    <stitle>ELECTRONIC ENGINE CONTROLS - DETROIT DIESEL SERIES 60 - 1992 - 1993 - DESCRIPTION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="0">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <para>The Detroit Diesel Series 60 is an electronically controlled, mechanically actuated, unit injected
                diesel engine. The Detroit Diesel Electronic Control (DDEC) system provides an electronic fuel control
                system, electronic engine protection and other operational controls.
            </para>
            <para>DDEC is standard on Series 60 engines and controls the following functions:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Road Speed Governor</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Cruise Control</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Remote Throttle PTO Control</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Automatic Idle Shutdown Timer (3 To 100 Minutes)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Engine Diagnostics</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Engine Protection System</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>Refer to the Detroit Diesel Manual furnished with the vehicle for additional information.</para>
            <para>Since each Series 60 DDEC system is electronically programmable to individual owner specifications,
                the operating parameters will vary from vehicle to vehicle. These parameters include: maximum cruise
                speed, maximum road speed setting, and many others.
            </para>
            <para>The "Brain" of the DDEC system is the ECM (electronic control module) located on the left side of the
                engine. The ECM receives input from the following components:
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Timing Reference Sensor (TRS)*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Synchronous Reference Sensor (SRS)*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS)**</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Throttle Position Sensor **</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Service Brake Switch**</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Park Brake Switch**</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Clutch Switch**</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Turbo Boost Sensor*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Coolant Level Probe**</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Coolant Level Sensor*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Fuel Temperature Sensor*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Oil Pressure Sensor*</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Oil Temperature Sensor*</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>* Detroit Diesel Installed Sensors</para>
            <para>** International Installed Sensors</para>
            <para>The ECM receives inputs from sensors and switches, then outputs signals to the injectors, engine brake
                relay and other system components.
            </para>
        </svcproc>
